will see the difference.} Bh6 29. Nc2 $1 {The knight can attack black's queen
or pawns from every direction.} Bg7 30. Nb4 Qc5 31. Qf3 $1 {Of course, no
endgames !} Ka7 32. Nd3 Qb6 (32... Qg5 33. h4 Qh6 34. Nf4) 33. Qxh5 Rec8 34.
Qg4 Bh8 35. Bxe6 $18 {We have just seen that to win a position with the safer
king, the first step is to stop the opponent's counterplay. Then, if you avoid
exchanges and continuously improve your pieces while repeatedly creating small
threats, you will inevitably accumulate an advantage on the clock. Your
opponent is obliged to carefully follow your actions and precisely calculate
possible tricks. Usually, the defender is doomed, unless he manages to create
counterplay or beat off the attack, for example by forcing exchanges. Due to
the limited time to think, the defender is unlikely to find an ingenious way
to change the flow of the game. If the defender attempts to solve the problems
he has, he risks to end up with nothing valuable, and his time will be gone
forever!} 1-0

