{After analysing many of Carlsen's blitz games, I realized how he imposes his
will on his opponents. Now I will present four of his games and explain how he
employs the domination technique to exert psychological pressure and provoke
mistakes. Magnus Carlsen, who is the world #1 in both classical and blitz, is
famous for his excellent endgame technique. He often outplays his opponents in
equal endgames and generally plays rather quiet chess more often than not. So
I was amazed to find how aggressive his approach is in blitz. I discovered
that he doesn't care much about creating pawn weaknesses in his own camp or
sacrificing material. In these four games I will focus on revealing how and at
what point of the game he starts to dominate - very often to such a degree
that his opponent is distracted from his strategic goals.} 1. d4 d5 2. c4 c6 3.
Nf3 Nf6 4. Nc3 e6 5. e3 Nbd7 6. Qc2 a5 {What we can see here is a weapon very
often used by Carlsen. Early in the opening he makes a new and rather
challenging move to create a situation in which his opponent doesn't feel
confident. This way he gains a time advantage and avoids any preparation by
his opponents.} 7. a4 {An equally strange answer.} (7. b3 {was the move to
challenge the rather meaningless 7.. a5, but White must be ready to meet} a4 8.
Nxa4 dxc4 9. Qxc4 $1 {, when Black doesn't have enough for the pawn.}) 7... Bd6
8. Be2 O-O 9. O-O dxc4 10. Bxc4 e5 11. Ba2 Qe7 12. h3 Bb4 $1 {Black doesn't
have much of a choice.} (12... Re8 13. Ng5) ({and} 12... h6 13. Nh4 {are very
bad, leaving only ...Bb4 and ...Kh8 as reasonable options.}) 13. dxe5 (13. Rd1)
13... Nxe5 14. Nd4 {I have often played similar positions with the black
pieces and I can tell that the only aggressive plan is to create pressure on
the kingside. At the same time, Black should take preventive measures to
discourage the advance of White's central pawns (f4, e4-e5).} c5 {Black's move
c6-c5 may be antipositional, but the knight on b5 will be far away from the
kingside - the main area of the action.} 15. Ndb5 Be6 $1 {White may have been
afraid for his bishop on a2, which could be cut off from play by c5-c4, and
happy to see Be6.} (15... c4 16. f4 Nc6 (16... Nd3 17. Bxc4 Nxc1 18. Qxc1) 17.
Bxc4 Bc5 18. Rf3 Nb4 19. Qf2 Bf5 {With decent compensation.}) 16. Bxe6 fxe6 $1
{Black has opened the f-file, therefore his rook is now actively participating
in the fight against White's main plan to advance his central pawns.} 17. e4 (
17. f4 {may be better, but with dark-squared bishops on the board, moves like
f4 are antipositional. Therefore it was easy to guess that Yu Yangyi would
play e4, which was part of his plan. White would like zo follow-up with Be3
and f4, hoping to achieve e4-e5 in the near future.}) 17... Nh5 $1 {Black
takes control of the f4-square and threatens Qh4.} 18. Ne2 $1 {Yu Yangyi takes
control of f4, showing that he is not afraid of Qh4.} (18. f4 {threatens
nothing, and after} c4 $1 19. Be3 Nd3 {, White's position falls apart.}) 18...
g5 $1 {Starting from the move c7-c5, both sides are involved in a sharp fight.
You can feel the heat. Now the threat is g5-g4, when Black's pieces will
threaten White's king's position.} (18... Qh4 {is unclear.} 19. Nc7 ({, or even
} 19. f4 $5) 19... Nf3+ 20. Kh1) 19. Be3 $2 {Black is threatening g5-g4, so it
is a bad idea to place the bishop on e3, as after 19... g4 20. hxg4 Nxg4 the
bishop would be attacked by the knight on g4.} (19. f4 {is ugly but necessary.}
) (19. Bd2 $1 g4 (19... Bxd2 20. Qxd2 g4 21. hxg4 Nxg4 22. f3) 20. Bc3 $3 Qg5 (
20... Bxc3 21. Qxc3 Qg5 22. hxg4) 21. Bxe5 Qxe5 22. hxg4) 19... g4 $1 {Now
