{This is perhaps the key game to opening your eyes for the main difference
between blitz and classical chess.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 d5 5.
cxd5 exd5 6. Bg5 h6 7. Bh4 O-O 8. e3 Bf5 9. Nd2 $146 {An interesting novelty
in this theoretically heavily charged position. White's idea is to cover the
e4 square to prevent the g5&Ne4 idea. Usually, White goes either} (9. Be2 Nbd7
10. Qb3 Bxc3+ 11. Qxc3 c6 12. Nd2 Ne4 {Grischuk,A -Karjakin,S Moscow 2019}) ({
or} 9. Qb3 Bxc3+ 10. Qxc3 Nbd7) 9... g5 10. Bg3 c5 $1 {Black immediately hits
d4, exploiting the drawbacks of White's knight move.} 11. a3 Bxc3 (11... Ba5 $5
) 12. bxc3 c4 (12... Qa5) (12... Nc6) 13. h4 $1 {Carlsen starts the domination
game. His main aim is to charge the position with tension around the
opponent's king.} g4 14. h5 $5 Nbd7 15. Bf4 {Refusing to develop more pieces
to instead approach Black's king immediately. In such positions, it is
impossible to build the attack the usual way, as there is just no time for
development. Before White develops all his pieces, Black would start his
counterattack on the queenside. So White attempts to take control of the game
by reaching the opponent's king first. Then, after already creating some
strong threats, there may be time for the other pieces to join.} Qa5 16. Qc1 $1
{The ideal place for the queen - defending c3 and at the same time looking
towards the kingside on the c1-h6 diagonal.} Nb6 {We saw the same picture in
the other five games. Instead of defending his king, Black is in a hurry to
start counterplay on the other wing. To impose his will on the opponent and
have his attack arrive first, Anand is ready to sacrifice not only the pawn on
h6 but also an exchange.} 17. Bxh6 Na4 {The crisis is approaching.} (17... Rfe8
$5) 18. Bxf8 Rxf8 {White won the exchange, but all his remaining pieces are
deeply frozen. How can he handle this problem?} 19. f3 $1 {Maybe Carlsen is
sending his king into the final attack? No - he is preparing e4, after which
White's queen will reach its final destination.} Re8 20. Kf2 $1 b5 21. e4 $1 {
White has only the king and the knight in play, but it appears that this is
more than enough to finish the game.} dxe4 22. Nxc4 $1 {The knight is
sacrificed for gain of time.} bxc4 23. Qg5+ Kh7 24. Qxf6 e3+ 25. Kg1 $1 {
back to the base} Be6 26. d5 $1 Qxd5 27. Re1 {This is the moment Magnus was
hoping for - he has strong threats against the opponent's king and Black's
pieces are busy with defence. Black has no time to counterattack, therefore
the rook can join the attack.} (27. fxg4 Bxg4 28. Rh4 Rg8 29. Qf4 $18) 27...
Qd2 28. Re2 Qc1 29. Qd4 gxf3 30. Qxe3 Qxc3 31. gxf3 Rg8+ 32. Kf2 {White hasn't
moved his bishop, nor his rook, yet his position is easily winning.} Qg7 33.
Qe4+ Kh6 34. Qf4+ Kh7 35. Qe5 Qh6 36. Rg1 Rc8 37. Qe4+ Kh8 38. Qd4+ Kh7 39.
Rxe6 $1 {Is it possible to play like this and win? 27 moves without moving any
rook? Has Carlsen been using some kind of hypnosis? After analysing those four
games, you should already be aware of the main point: Playing blitz is all
about putting pressure on the opponent. If you can pressure him continuously
by creating threats around his king, he will never be able to relax and focus
on achieving his goals. And don't forget one important thing: In blitz, time
on the clock is no less important than what's objectively happening on the
board. And creating an attack also means gaining time. Attacking is usually
much easier and less risky than defending, and as a result, the player who
exerts pressure and forces his will on his opponent is likely to gain a
significant advantage on the clock. To help you improve your domination skills,
