{Now I will focus on the camouflage technique. It is very difficult to acquire,
but also very useful, as it pays off well in blitz. To master the camouflage,
you should learn to apply the following simple idea. Imagine a situation in
which you have a couple of good-looking and practically equivalent
alternatives. If possible, quickly choose the move which looks like you are
doing nothing special, but sets some kind of hidden trap. Let's take a look at
a recent game between Carlsen and Mamedyarov. At the critical point of the
game, after 10. Qf3, Mamedyarov could have created immediate counterplay in
the centre by 10..Qc7, but instead he prefered to apply the camouflage move 10.
.Rc8.} 1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 Nf6 3. e3 e6 4. Nf3 Bd6 {This time Carlsen takes a
different choice than in game 3, and again different from the classical Bg3 -
the typical technique of posing different problems every time. The difference
may look very small, but the opponent has to think and compare the
consequences of every line.} 5. Nbd2 O-O 6. c3 b6 7. Ne5 c5 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. h4 {
The most aggressive approach. Carlsen is ready to show the main attacking
ideas of the London system.} (9. Qf3 $1 {, to avoid Ne4, may be even stronger.}
) 9... Nc6 (9... Ne4 $5) 10. Qf3 {White's pieces are slowly approaching the
opponent's king, and it is White's primary intention to deliver checkmate.
What should Black do in such a situation? How to meet this kind of obvious
domination attempt?} Rc8 $5 {With this move, Mamedyarov signals courage and
disrespect for what Carlsen is doing, seemingly not caring about his kingside.
But he is doing much more than that. Of course, an aggressive player like him
would not just sit and watch while his opponent is advancing the kingside
pawns. With Rc8, Mamedyarov is applying what I call the camouflage technique.
It can be described in the following way: To make a useful and logical move,
often just a small improvement of your position, waiting for the opponent to
continue with his most natural move as well. In this case, Mamedyarov is
waiting for g2-g4, which is White's most natural way to develop pressure on
the kingside. When your opponent makes the desired move, the camouflage can be
disclosed - usually by means of a hidden trick, punishing the opponent for
what turns out to be a mistake. In this position, there was a more direct way
to escape domination by immediate counterplay in the centre after} (10... Qc7
$1 11. Nxc6 (11. Qg3 $2 Nh5) 11... Bxc6 12. Bxd6 Qxd6 {, and if} 13. g4 {
, Black has} e5 $1 $132) 11. h5 $1 {Seeing through the camouflage! Usually in
this kind of position, White instantly goes for g4-g5, but Carlsen knows that
his opponent is an extremely tricky player and would never play a passive move
like Rc8 without having something in mind. Carlsen has huge experience with
players like Mamedyarov, Nakamura and Nepo, and he smelled that something was
wrong here. Intuitively, he decided that it just can't be good to open the
diagonal against the Bb7. Still, Mamdyarov continues with his camouflage play.}
(11. g4 $2 Bxe5 12. dxe5 Nd7 13. Qg3 d4 $132) 11... h6 {Here Mamedyarov might
have better taken on d4, preparing his counterattack.} (11... cxd4 12. exd4
Bxe5 13. dxe5 Nd7 14. Qg3 Kh8 15. h6 (15. O-O-O $5)) ({It is too late for} 
11... Qc7 12. Qg3 $1) ({Also,} 11... Kh8 {is not good due to} 12. h6 g6 13. Bg5
Be7 14. Bxf6+ Bxf6 15. Nd7 $18) 12. Qg3 $1 {It looks like there is no defence
against Bh6.} Ne8 $1 {Preparing a clever trick.} (12... Kh8 $2 13. Ng6+) (12...
cxd4 13. exd4 Ne8 14. Bxh6 Nxe5 15. dxe5 Bxe5 16. f4) 13. Bxh6 cxd4 $2 {
Mamedyarov probably expected that Carlsen would automatically take back on d4,
and he certainly missed the following cruel treatment. Otherwise, he would
have immediately taken on e5, which was better without the inclusion of cd4.} (
13... Nxe5 $1 {was the only move.} 14. dxe5 Bxe5 $1 15. Qxe5 (15. f4 Bxc3 $1 {
This is the main point of Black's defence.} 16. bxc3 Qf6 $1 $132 17. Bg5 Qxc3
18. Ke2 c4 19. Bb1 d4 $19) 15... gxh6 16. Rh3 Qf6 $1 {And Black is well alive.}
) (13... f6 14. Bxg7 Nxg7 15. h6 $18) 14. Bxg7 $1 {Suddenly it is all over.
This time the deception and camouflage were not successful.} Nxg7 15. h6 Qf6 (
15... Bxe5 16. Bh7+ $3 {is the trick that Mamedyarov missed.}) 16. hxg7 (16.
Bh7+) (16. Qxg7+) 16... Qxg7 17. Bh7+ Kh8 18. Nxf7+ Rxf7 19. Bg6+ Kg8 20. Bxf7+
Kxf7 21. Qxd6 $18 {Mamedyarov had a couple of chances to stay in the game, but
he missed them. His attempt to mislead his opponent didn't work and his
counterattack came too late. He prepared it very carefully with moves like Rc8,
h6 and Ne8, but when the right moment came, his opponent was faster.} *

