{At the end of my article, I would like to turn your attention to the opening
preparation, which is an important element for success in blitz. You need to
prepare a couple of early alternatives aiming to put your opponents at bay at
the start of the game. This will help you a lot to gain confidence and at the
same time will cut off the opponent's opening preparation. I prepared some
ideas that you can use in your games, followed by small tests: Can you find
the novelty? I know that many are struggling to find an antidote to the
Hippopotamus system. It is quite annoying to see your opponent play his first
15 moves quickly and independently of what you are doing. Soon you will find
yourself in a situation where you exceeded your useful moves and need to do
something concrete. So you inevitably stop for a while to work out a plan,
reach a good position, but lose on time. To avoid this kind of scenario, take
a look at the following game.} 1. e4 g6 2. d4 d6 3. Nf3 Bg7 4. Be2 {White
plays classical chess while Black is still pretending to play a Pirc Defence.
Playing against Nakamura, you can expect that he will not stick to the usual
development pattern of Nf6, 0-0, c6, Nbd7, which leaves you with a risk-free
minimal advantage in a quiet position. Predictably, Nakamura goes for a Hippo.}
e6 $1 (4... Nf6 5. Nc3 O-O 6. O-O c6 7. Re1 $1 $14) 5. O-O {[%cal Re1g1]} h6 6.
c4 $1 g5 (6... Ne7 7. Nc3 O-O 8. Be3 f5 9. Qd2 g5 10. exf5 exf5 (10... Nxf5 11.
g4 $1 Nxe3 12. fxe3 $40) 11. d5 f4 12. Bd4 g4 13. Bxg7 gxf3 14. Bxf8 fxe2 15.
Nxe2 Qxf8 16. Nxf4 $18) 7. Nc3 Ne7 {Black enjoys the freedom to play his own
game that is so typical for the Hippo. But now White will set an end to this,
disrupting his easy and automatic play with early activity.} 8. h4 $1 {
Starting the opening in a classical way doesn't mean you have to follow-up in
the same style.} g4 9. Ne1 h5 (9... Ng6 10. h5) 10. Bg5 $1 {This is a highly
important move, to prevent Black's counterattack with Ng6.} f6 (10... Nd7 11.
f3 f6 12. Be3 gxf3 13. Bxf3) 11. Be3 O-O {Black is forced to castle, as White
was threatening to break through with f3.} 12. d5 $1 (12. f3 f5 13. Bg5 Nbc6
14. Nc2 Qe8 15. fxg4 hxg4 16. Qd2) 12... f5 13. Bg5 Qe8 14. c5 $1 {Black
collapses - the Hippo was badly crushed.} (14. Nd3 $18) 14... fxe4 (14... dxc5
15. Nd3 b6 16. Nf4 e5 (16... exd5 17. Ncxd5) 17. d6) 15. cxd6 cxd6 16. dxe6 (
16. Nxe4 Nxd5 17. Nxd6 Qd7 18. Ne4) 16... Bxe6 (16... Nbc6 17. Nxe4 Bxe6 18.
Nxd6) 17. Nxe4 Nf5 18. Nd3 $5 (18. Nxd6 Nxd6 19. Qxd6 Nc6 20. Nd3 Nd4) 18...
Nc6 (18... Bc4 19. Ng3 Nxg3 20. fxg3 Nd7 21. Rxf8+ Nxf8 22. Nf4 Bxe2 23. Nxe2
Ng6 24. Qxd6 Qxe2 25. Qxg6 Rf8 26. Rc1) 19. Nf4 {With such an open king, Black
is hopeless.} Ncd4 20. Bd3 Be5 21. Re1 Qf7 22. Nxd6 $1 {The final touch!} Bxd6
23. Bxf5 Nxf5 24. Nxe6 Rfe8 25. Qb3 g3 26. fxg3 Nxg3 27. Re3 Rac8 28. Rae1 Rc6
29. Rf3 Qg6 30. Nc7+ {Great game and an amazing idea that is useful against
all kind of Hippo setups.} 1-0

